# Autonomous Developer Rule

When modifying this Unity project, behave as a **safe autonomous developer**. Follow this workflow and constraints every time.

## 1. Read AI Documentation First

Before writing or changing any code:

- Read **Docs/ai/PROJECT_OVERVIEW.md** (purpose, gameplay loop, architecture, folder structure).
- Read **Docs/ai/CODING_RULES.md** (naming, MonoBehaviour, performance, structure).
- Read **Docs/ai/MODULE_REGISTRY.yaml** (module paths, dependencies, `editable`, `risk`).

If the user request is ambiguous, infer intent from these docs. Do not add code that contradicts them.

## 2. Plan Before Implementing

For every feature or change:

1. **Write a short PLAN** (bullet list or numbered steps) before editing files.
2. Include: target module(s), new types/classes if any, and which existing types you will reuse or extend.
3. Only after the plan is clear, start implementing.

Do not implement large features in one shot without a visible plan.

## 3. Map Every Feature to a Module

- Each feature must belong to **exactly one** existing or new module listed in **MODULE_REGISTRY.yaml**.
- If the feature spans multiple domains, pick the **primary** module and use dependencies (e.g. Shared, other modules) without creating unlisted top-level modules.
- To add a **new module**: add an entry to **MODULE_REGISTRY.yaml** (name, path, editable, risk, description, dependencies) and create code only under **Assets/Game/Modules/<ModuleName>/**.
- Respect **editable: false** (e.g. Core): do not modify that module unless the user **explicitly allows** it.

## 4. New Code Only Under Assets/Game/Modules

- **All new code** (scripts, ScriptableObjects, etc.) must live under **Assets/Game/Modules/** (e.g. `Assets/Game/Modules/Combat`, `Assets/Game/Modules/Economy`).
- Exception: **Shared** types and interfaces may live under **Assets/Game/Shared** when they are cross-module contracts.
- Do not create new top-level folders or scripts outside `Assets/Game/` that bypass the module registry.

## 5. Never Modify Core Unless Explicitly Allowed

- **Do not** add, edit, or delete files under **Assets/Game/Core/** unless the user explicitly says so (e.g. "you may change Core" or "add X to Core").
- Core is `editable: false` and `risk: high`. Treat it as read-only for normal feature work.
- If a feature logically belongs in Core, propose it and ask for explicit permission before touching Core.

## 6. Avoid Large Scene or Prefab Modifications

- Prefer **small, localized** changes to scenes and prefabs (e.g. adding a component, wiring one reference).
- Avoid bulk edits, mass renames, or structural overhauls of scenes/prefabs unless the user explicitly requests them.
- When possible, implement behavior in **new or existing prefabs** and keep scene hierarchy changes minimal.

## 7. Generate at Least One Test for New Modules

- When **creating a new module** (new folder under `Assets/Game/Modules/<ModuleName>` with new scripts):
  - Add **at least one test** (e.g. EditMode or PlayMode test in `Assets/Game/Modules/<ModuleName>/Tests` or project test folder) that covers the main entry point or a critical path of that module.
- For **existing modules**: add or extend tests when adding non-trivial behavior, when the user asks for tests, or when the change is risky.

## 8. Summarize Changes and Risk After Edits

After completing code (or doc) changes, post a **short summary** that includes:

- **Modified files**: list of paths (e.g. `Assets/Game/Modules/Combat/Health.cs`, `Docs/ai/MODULE_REGISTRY.yaml`).
- **Risk level**: `low` | `medium` | `high` (aligned with MODULE_REGISTRY and scope of change).
- Optional: one-line description per file or per module touched.

Example:

```
Summary:
- Modified: Assets/Game/Modules/Economy/CurrencyService.cs, Assets/Game/Modules/Economy/CurrencyWallet.cs
- New: Assets/Game/Modules/Economy/Tests/CurrencyServiceTests.cs
- Risk: medium (Economy module, no Core change)
```

This rule works together with **Docs/ai/CODING_RULES.md** and **Docs/ai/MODULE_REGISTRY.yaml**. When in doubt, prefer safety: no Core edits, small prefab/scene changes, and a clear plan before implementation.
